values: i just accidentally listened to some old Tim McGraw song on itunes and i had these vivid memories of 10th grade. It made me a little sad...especially considering I've been talking to Berkley a lot lately. 10th grade was a really fun year. i wish i had more pictures. And a better memory.

i guess i have no reason to stay in los angeles anymore. the industry that i had planned to speed my life working in now bores me. and the life i had in la is no longer my life. someone will fill my shoes...but will she'll fill them completely, which i was incapable of doing. everyone's lives will go on. probably in a much better way than they are now. 

at least she finally admitted what i've known for a long time...that i make her miserable and that she's better without me. that makes me feel a little better, like i'm doing the right thing. but then it also makes me feel worse than anything else has ever felt in my life. It's not like I didn't know that's what I made a person feel like because I HAVE known for months (if not longer). How could I not have known? It wasn't like the feelings were really hidden. But they were always denied until tonight. So in some ways it's a relief knowing, but, like I said, it also hurts more than I thought anything could possibly hurt. 

but it's an excuse to leave la, i guess. maybe i could even come back to ny. i forgot how much i missed it. but most of the time i feel like my life in ny ended. i don't need to move back. it's my past. there are other places other than la. not only because i hate los angeles, but because the thought of ever seeing her with someone else makes my skin crawl. it makes me want to scream. i never want to have to experience that. everywhere i go will have some sort of ghost that reminds me of the person with whom i thought i'd spend my entire life. 

i have to fly 'home' tomorrow. everyone keeps trying to get me to extend my ticket and stay longer. as much as i'd like to, i really just need to go home so i can cry in my own bed.

katie, your sense of humor is Sarcasm

Oh yeah, you're really funny. (Actually you are, but you're so sarcastic that it's hard to tell when you're joking.) You mean what you say, but almost never say exactly what you mean. In fact you usually say the exact opposite. For instance, if your friend is wearing an ugly watch, you might tell them, "I wanted a watch like that once, but I got the wrong Happy Meal." Yep, there's a slight edge to your humor, but all you are really doing is telling it like it is, only like it's not.

Whether you're roasting a friend or playing social critic, your deadpan delivery and dry cynicism go a long way to expressing your true feelings...and making people laugh along the way.

katie, you're an Elephant in the wild world of love.

You're a favorite amongst any herd, aren't you, my little Elephant? Like your animal alter ego, you're probably more devoted, family-oriented, and loyal than your average creature roaming the jungle of love. For you, mating is probably more about expressing your feelings than just satisfying sexual urges. Overall, you're great with people, and you always seem to have a story or comment that leaves the group feeling better about things.

You're cuter than Dumbo, and smarter too, which is why hanging out with you is always a good time. Despite all the attention, however, you're probably not one to charge ahead into a romantic encounter without thinking first. You prefer to be friends first before letting things heat up. the other day i was getting a facial and for some reason i started thinking about my apartment in ny. like every inch of it trying to remember it exactly. and then i kept thinking "i'll never have that apartment again." Something about that made me sad. It was the perfect NY apartment. The perfect location. The perfect apartment at that time. I kept remembering that one summer Carroll and Josh lived in it with me and how we'd have to write Josh notes to turn off the oven. And how we made THE dip so much. And how much I hated the grocery store that was the closest to us because it was closed on Sundays and also because it was mexican and it didn't fit in on the upper west side. And how it had tons of closets but they were ridiculously small and oddly shaped. And how you could watch the Thanksgiving Day Parade from if you stuck your head out of the window or got on the fire escape. And how we named all of our across the street neighbors. I wonder where "Kathy" and "Steven" are now. And how Monica and Holly came over one night after work to watch FRIENDS and they couldn't believe my stockpile of black beans. And how Eddie, the Super, would turn on the heat really high and I'd open my windows when it was snowing out and it felt perfect. I had on a mas during said facial when I was thinking this and I cried. Because I'll never have that apartment again. That was the apartment that felt like home. I lived in 2 others ones in the city for 2 different summers, but neither ever felt like home. That was the apartment that made New York City feel like the only place in the world. I missed Lennys, and the city grill, and Harrys, and that italian restaurant on 66th and Columbus, across from ABC and the movie theater, and Rays, and the sunday flea market across the street from my building, and that one summer I rode my bike in central park, and trying to buy the handcuffs from dress up in Webers but being told they were for people who tried to steal and not for sale. I think I missed that time in my life moreso that that actual apartment. I guess I realized I can never have that again, even if I wanted it. Sometimes I just miss my past. I miss these random moments in my past. Like rushing from work one day to go to the shoe sale at Bergdorf with Monica and Holly. And drinking at Dukes with them, during a snowstorm. And meeting a stranger named jc and carroll getting in a fight in some bar called Martinis that no longer exists when it was blizzarding and work and schools were closed. And buying a subway map in a store in the world trade center and then a month later watching it collapse. And then being dragged down to the rubble by my parents when all I wanted to do was scream at all the tourist assholes for making it a tourist attraction. it was a mass grave. not somewhere to file by, taking pictures. To this day I hate that I did it. I also hate that I didn't volunteer to help look for people and things immediately following. I hate myself for that. My school sent some people to help and I could have gone and I didn't. 
Anyway, something really triggered these memories of this other life I had. It's not to say I don't like my life now. Well, I hate where I live and I don't feel settled like I have at every other point in my life but I do like my life with the ladyfriend. And I wouldn't trade that. I guess I'm just really happy that I had that New York experience. It was perfect. I doubt if I ever moved back there it would be the same. My life isn't the same. I'm not in the same place. It was perfect when it happened and the way it happened. 

I forgot how good cold weather feels. It's somewhat cold (40s) in Seattle right now. I love walking out into that.
